<h1>2.5.3 Demonstrative pronouns</h1>
<p>Status: <em>draft</em>: tranls. + disc.</p>
<h2 id="relevant-postag-codes">Relevant postag codes:</h2>
<p><strong>Position and letters in postag string:</strong></p>
<ol type="1">
<li><p>part of speech: <strong>1st</strong>; letter: <strong>p</strong>
(pronoun)</p></li>
<li><p>number: <strong>3rd</strong>; letters: <strong>s</strong>
(singular), <strong>d</strong> (dual), <strong>p</strong>
(plural)</p></li>
<li><p>gender: <strong>7th</strong>; letters: <strong>m</strong>
(masculine), <strong>f</strong> (feminine), <strong>n</strong>
(neuter)</p></li>
<li><p>case: <strong>8th</strong>; letters: <strong>n</strong>
(nominative), <strong>g</strong> (genitive), <strong>d</strong>
(dative), <strong>a</strong> (accusative), <strong>v</strong>
(vocative)</p></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Example postag string:</strong> p-s—mn- (pronoun, singular,
masculine, nominative)</p>
<p>See <a href="https://papygreek.com/grammar/106">4.5.3</a> for the use
of the demonstrative pronoun and <a href="https://papygreek.com/grammar/96">6.6</a> for the order of the
demonstrative and noun.</p>
<h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
<p>The declension table for the demonstrative pronouns can be found in
<a data-link-newtab="" href="/smyth/body.1_div1.2_div2.6.html" data-url="smyth/body.1_div1.2_div2.6.html">Smyth §333</a>.</p>
<p>The most common demonstrative pronouns (or deictic pronouns) are:</p>
<ul>
<li>ὅδε, ἥδε, τόδε (hóde, hḗde, tóde) <em>this (here)</em></li>
<li>οὗτος, αὗτη, τοῦτο (hoûtos, haütē, toûto) <em>this</em>,
<em>that</em> (here),</li>
<li>ἐκεῖνος, ἐκείνη, ἐκεῖνο (ekeînos, ekeínē, ekeîno) <em>that
(there)</em>.</li>
</ul>
<p>The first two refer to something close by, whereas ἐκεῖνος refers to
something farther away.</p>
